{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Researchers cite several reasons for the disparity, including evidence of racial bias and stereotyping. The lower level of treatment tends to lead to more disability....", "abstract": "Research shows minorities receive less pain treatment from doctors than whites, and often suffer more long-term disablity as result; studies have found evidence of racial bias and stereotyping, both consciously and unconsciously, in recognizing and treating pain among minorities, particularly black patients.", "section_name": "U.S.", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Abby", "role": "reported", "lastname": "GOODNOUGH", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By ABBY GOODNOUGH", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/10/us/how-race-plays-a-role-in-patients-pain-treatment.html", "lead_paragraph": "Researchers cite several reasons for the disparity, including evidence of racial bias and stereotyping. The lower level of treatment tends to lead to more disability.", "headline": {"main": "Finding Good Pain Treatment Is Hard. If You\u2019re Not White, It\u2019s Even Harder.", "print_headline": "Minorities Seeking Pain Relief Are Shortchanged in Treatment"}, "_id": "57aa4c5a95d0e021d797f759", "word_count": "1473", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/08/06/us/00pain-web1/00pain-web1-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/08/06/us/00pain-web1/00pain-web1-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 400, "url": "images/2016/08/06/us/00pain-web1/00pain-web1-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/08/06/us/00pain-web1/00pain-web1-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "400"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2016/08/06/us/00pain-web1/00pain-web1-thumbStandard.jpg", "legacy": {"thumbnail": "images/2016/08